More geometries that can help to visualise uncertainty

  • The ribbon plot
  • Box-plots
  • Violin plots
  • Jitter plots

The ribbon plot

  • Plots are a good way of communicating simply, but sometimes we want to express uncertainty

The ribbon plot

You need three aesthetics: 1. x: the value along the x axis 2. ymin: the minumum of the ribbon. Typically calculated using quantile() 3. ymax: the maximum of the ribbon. Ditot.

I often add lines over the top of the ribbon, normally the median or the mean, using geom_line().

Exercise

Note: You can pass aesthetics either to the main ggplot() call, or inside the geom_x() calls

  • Using the data apra.sr.full, in each year, calculate the median, 25th percentile, and 75th percentile of Rate_of_return.
    • If I wanted to calculate the 30th percentile of x, I can use quantile(x, 0.3).
  • generate a ribbon plot of the annual returns.
  • inside geom_ribbon, set fill = "acolour"; also perhaps use some alpha.
  • Plot a line over the top of the ribbon that shows the median return in each year. - Change the theme to something pretty

The box plot

  • Widely used, and relatively easy to understand.
    • The line in the middle is the median
    • The box is the inter-quartile range (contains the middle 50% of the data)
    • the lines run from the 10th percentile to the 90th, containing 80% of observations
    • Outliers are beyond that.

The box plot

  • Requires two aesthetics: x and y; x must be of categorical form (a factor)
apra.sr.full %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = as.factor(Year), y = Rate_of_return)) +
  geom_boxplot()

The violin plot

  • Very similar to the box plot
  • Perhaps easier to read?
  • Definitely easy to compare distributions

The violin plot

  • Requires two aesthetics: x and y; x must be of categorical form (a factor)
apra.sr.full %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = as.factor(Year), y = Rate_of_return)) +
  geom_violin()

The jitter plot

  • Rather than summarising the data using a box or a violin, why not plot the data?
apra.sr.full %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = as.factor(Year), y = Rate_of_return)) +
  geom_point()

The jitter plot

  • The jitter plot offsets the data along the x axis by some random amount, meaning we can see all the data points. 
apra.sr.full %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = as.factor(Year), y = Rate_of_return)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.4)

Writing your own themes

  • Relatively straighforward
    • Easiest way is to start with a theme that you'd like to build on
    • Go into the source code or github, copy it, and make some changes
    • Also can copy the basic ones here:
    • http://sape.inf.usi.ch/quick-reference/ggplot2/themes

Basic mapping

  • Using GIS tools in R is an entire short-course in itself.
  • What you should be aware of is that there is a lot of GIS libraries for R, and they deal with all major geographic data types (shape-files, coordinates, projections, etc.).
  • The easiest to use ones plug straight into Google Maps and OpenStreetMaps.
  • We'll have a little play with ggmaps, a mapping plug-in for ggplot2.

ggmap

  • ggmap is an incredibly easy and powerful package
library(ggmap)
melb <- get_map("Melbourne", zoom = 12)
ggmap(melb)

ggmap

Add some points to the plot. 

code <- geocode(location = c("205 Alma Road St Kilda East"))
melb <- get_map("Melbourne, Australia", zoom = 12) 

ggmap(melb) + geom_point(aes(x = code$lon, y = code$lat), colour = "red")

ggmap

Add a path

code <- geocode(location = c("205 Alma Road St Kilda East", "20 Queen St Melbourne"))
melb <- get_googlemap("Melbourne, Australia", markers = code, path = code,zoom = 12) 
ggmap(melb)

ggmap

Make it sexy

code <- geocode(location = c("205 Alma Road St Kilda East", "20 Queen St Melbourne"))
melb <- get_googlemap("Melbourne, Australia", markers = code, path = code,zoom = 12, maptype = "satellite") 
ggmap(melb)

ggvis

  • ggplot2 is awesome, but it was designed for paper & presentation
  • A lot of content is now viewed in web browsers; why not use this additional functionality?
  • D3 gives amazing functionality, but javascript is not designed for data prep & analysis; it's nice to have everything in the same environment.
  • ggvis makes this easy, and has syntax inspired by ggplot2. It also plays nicely with dplyr.

ggvis

library(ggvis)
apra.sr.full %>% ggvis(x = ~as.factor(Year), y = ~Rate_of_return, fill = ~Fund_type) %>%
  layer_points()

  • Renderer: SVG | Canvas

ggvis

Let's add some interactivity. In this first case, we'll allow the user to change the size of the points. 

library(ggvis); library(dplyr)
apra.sr.full %>% ggvis(x = ~as.factor(Year), y = ~Rate_of_return, fill = ~Fund_type, size := input_slider(20, 200), opacity := input_slider(0,1)) %>%
  layer_points()

ggvis

Let's add some more interactivity. In this second case, we'll let the user run a smoother for each group

library(ggvis); library(dplyr)
apra.sr.full %>% ggvis(x = ~Year, y = ~Rate_of_return) %>%
  layer_smooths(span = input_slider(min= 0.2, max = 1))

ggvis: very cool, very underdeveloped so far

  • This is a very new tool, and it looks to have load of promise
  • Yet it's still very un-polished.
    • Many missing features (no groups, no faceting, limited geometries)
    • By contrast, ggplot2 is amazingly mature
